Visualize Distribution of Genotypes (a.k.a. biomarkers)

filtered_biomark <- biomark %>%
  select(c(1:7, 16:17))  # Selecting columns relevant to analysis

# Function to determine genotype
get_genotype <- function(subjid) {
  sublist <- as.list(filtered_biomark[filtered_biomark$SUBJID == subjid, ][, c(3, 5, 7, 9)])
  if ("Mutant" %in% sublist) {
    return("Mutant")
  } else if ((sum(sublist == "Wild-type") > sum(sublist == "Unknown")) | 
             (sum(sublist == "Wild-type") > sum(sublist == "Failure")) |
             (sum(sublist == "Wild-type") > sum(sublist == "")) # OH: need to include empty set
             ) {
    return("Wild-type")
  } else {
    return("Unknown")
  }
}

filtered_biomark$Genotype <- sapply(filtered_biomark$SUBJID, get_genotype)

summary_df <- as.data.frame(table(filtered_biomark$Genotype))
colnames(summary_df) <- c("Category", "Count")

should we include predictive/ prognostic analysis done in HW2 to show where weâre picking up from? we know from HW2 that genotype is prognostic but not predictive (genotype impacts death outcome but this is not exacerbated by treatment). so we know that mutants are more likely to die (prognostic), but donât know how many fewer days they will live. And we know that mutants are not more likely to die when being treated (predictive), but we do not know how much longer mutant & wild-types live while on treatment. We set out to answer these questions:

Visualize how many deaths occured during the study and how long people lived, by genotype

d = left_join(filtered_biomark, 
              adsl[, c("SUBJID", "ATRT", "DTH", "DTHDY")], 
              by = "SUBJID")

Does the combination of Genotype and Treatment Arm have a significant impact on patient survival outcomes?

# Filtering out unknown genotypes since these are not informative for this analysis
dcombo <- subset(d, Genotype != "Unknown")

dcombo$Genotype = factor(dcombo$Genotype, ordered = FALSE)
dcombo$Genotype = relevel(dcombo$Genotype, ref = "Wild-type")

dcombo$ATRT = factor(dcombo$ATRT, ordered = FALSE)
dcombo$ATRT = relevel(dcombo$ATRT, ref = "FOLFOX alone")

surv_plot <- ggsurvplot(
  survfit(Surv(DTHDY, DTH) ~ Genotype + ATRT, data = dcombo),
  data = dcombo,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  legend.title = "Genotype & ATRT",
  title = "Kaplan-Meier Survival Curve by Genotype & Treatment Arm",
  xlab = "Time in Days",
  ylab = "Survival Probability",
  pval = TRUE
)

surv_plot$plot + geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, col = 'red')

Here we can see the following:

  • There are some statistically significant interactions with p < 0.0001 although it is not specified what those interactions are.

  • Subjects with a âWild-typeâ genotype generally show higher survival rates over time.

  • Subjects with a âMutantâ genotype generally show lower survival rates over time.

  • If a subject has the âWild-typeâ genotype, they may have an improved survival rate if they receive âPanitumumab+FOLFOXâ instead of âFOLFOX aloneâ

  • If a subject has the âMutantâ genotype, they may have an improved survival rate if they receive âFOLFOX aloneâ instead of âPanitumumab+FOLFOXâ

âDoes the presence of KRAS mutations significantly impact the survival outcomes of metastatic colorectal cancer patients receiving different treatment regimens, specifically Panitumumab in combination with FOLFOX and FOLFOX alone?â

  1. Cox Proportional Hazards Model:
    • The coefficient for dcombo$GenotypeMutant is 0.39534, which is positive. This positive coefficient suggests that having the âMutantâ genotype is associated with a higher hazard (risk) of death compared to the âWild-typeâ reference group.
  2. Log-Rank Test:
    • The log-rank test for the âGenotypeâ variable has a very small p-value (p=8e-07). This suggests that there is a significant difference in survival between different genotypes.

Patients with the âMutantâ genotype have a lower chance of survival compared to those with the âWild-typeâ genotype, as indicated by the positive coefficient and the significant log-rank test.

Are there differences in the occurrence of adverse events between patients receiving Panitumumab in combination with FOLFOX and those receiving FOLFOX alone?

The following code adds the number of unique adverse events per patient and examines whether there is a difference in this number by genotype or treatment:

adverse_events_temp <- adae |>
  group_by(SUBJID, AEPT) |>
  summarize(n = n())
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'SUBJID'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
adverse_events_per_subject <- adverse_events_temp |>
  group_by(SUBJID) |>
  summarize(adverse_events = n())

d_ae <- d |>
  left_join(adverse_events_per_subject, by = "SUBJID")

d_ae$adverse_events <- if_else(is.na(d_ae$adverse_events), 0, d_ae$adverse_events)
  
mutant_adverse_events <- d_ae |>
  filter(Genotype == "Mutant") |>
  select(adverse_events)

wild_type_adverse_events <- d_ae |>
  filter(Genotype == "Wild-type") |>
  select(adverse_events)

Wild-type and mutant genotypes do not have different numbers of adverse events during the trial (p>0.05). However, we did find that patients taking Folfox alone had an average of 2 fewer adverse events than patients taking both Folfox combined with Panitumumab (p<0.05).

chi_squared_test <- chisq.test(contingency_table)

Are there significant differences in the survival distribution over time between different genotypes?

Hypothesis: Null Hypothesis (H0): There is no significant difference in the survival distribution over time among different genotypes. Alternative Hypothesis (H1): There are significant differences in the survival distribution over time among different genotypes.

surv_diff_genotype <- survdiff(Surv(DTHDY, DTH) ~ Genotype, data = d)
